Natural disasters and emergencies — floods, fires, earthquakes, or accidents — require fast, coordinated responses, but affected individuals often don't know where to turn for help, where the nearest emergency services are, or how to alert others nearby about a developing situation. Emergency response teams, in turn, often lack a single, real-time view of where help is needed most, relying instead on scattered phone calls and fragmented reports that slow down response times when every minute counts. A centralized digital platform that connects people in distress with emergency services and real-time situational updates can significantly improve coordination and response speed during a crisis. PROBLEM STATEMENT Develop a platform that enables users to report emergencies, request assistance, locate nearby emergency services, and share real-time updates during natural disasters or other crisis situations. The platform should help both affected individuals and responders act quickly with better, more accurate information. WHO WILL USE THIS • Residents in disaster-prone areas who need a fast way to report and request help • Local emergency responders, NGOs, and volunteer groups coordinating relief efforts • Municipal or district authorities monitoring unfolding emergency situations CORE FEATURES ▸ User registration and login — Allow both citizens and responders to use the platform with appropriate roles. ▸ Emergency reporting — Let users quickly report an emergency with type, description, and location. ▸ Request assistance — Allow affected individuals to formally request help and track its status. ▸ Nearby services locator — Show the closest hospitals, shelters, police stations, or fire services on a map. ▸ Real-time updates feed — Share live situational updates from users and responders during a crisis. ▸ Simple, map-based interface — Make critical information easy to access quickly under stress. BONUS FEATURES (OPTIONAL) ★ Live incident heatmap — Visualize the density and severity of reported incidents across an area. ★ Volunteer coordination — Let verified volunteers sign up to assist with specific reported needs. ★ Offline/low-connectivity mode — Allow basic reporting even with poor network conditions during a disaster. ★ Multi-agency dashboard — Give authorities a unified view across all active incidents and requests. ★ Automated alert broadcasting — Push emergency notifications to users in an affected area. WHY THIS PROBLEM STATEMENT • Maps API — practical experience with geolocation, mapping, and location-based features. • Real-time updates — a strong use case for live data feeds and instant notifications. • Social impact — addresses a problem with direct, tangible benefit to people's safety. • Multiple implementation approaches — flexible scope lets teams pick their own technical angle.


